ide the Chest and Nodal Status\",\n      \"explanation\": \"A major insight from the protocol is the early bifurcation based on the presence of disease outside the chest, captured by entities and relationships involving 'Disease outside chest?' and 'Disease outside chest.' Patients with extrathoracic metastases (detected via staging workup) are triaged to advanced/metastatic management (NSCL-19), while those with disease confined within the chest undergo detailed nodal assessment (N0–1 vs N2–3), which influences the treatment direction—either initial local therapy or transition to systemic therapy for advanced disease. This critical triage, supported by protocol step relationships, underlines the importance of accurate staging in NSCLC care [Data: Entities (57, 56, 59, 60, 124, 125); Relationships (114, 116, 117, 123, 125)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Role of Histologic Subtype and Biomarker Testing in Advanced/Metastatic NSCLC\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Within the advanced/metastatic disease protocol (NSCL-19), emphasis is placed on establishing histologic subtype (adenocarcinoma, large cell, squamous) and performing comprehensive biomarker testing. The protocol mandates adequate tissue sourcing, rebiopsy or plasma-based testing as needed, and specific assessments (EGFR, ALK, KRAS, ROS1, BRAF, NTRK1/2/3, MET, RET, ERBB2, HER2, NRG1, PD-L1, c-Met IHC), increasingly driving personalized therapy. The structured relationships demonstrate the sequential process—first, histology is established, then corresponding biomarker testing is performed, and results feed directly into further treatment algorithms. This reflects a guideline-driven, evidence-based approach to maximize patient benefit and resource utilization [Data: Entities (124, 126, 127, 128, 129, 130, 131, 132); Relationships (289, 291, 292, 294, 295, 296, 297)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Standard Pathways for Multiple Scenario Management: Separate Nodules, Staging, and Surgery\",\n    